					<div class='post entry-content '>
						<!--cached-Tue, 22 Feb 2011 03:09:22 +0000--><p class='citation'>Holly Moore, on Nov 10 2008, 06&#58;47 PM, said:</p><div class="blockquote"><div class='quote'>Great presentation Steven.<br />
<br />
One thought - instead of dumping the unneeded rendered fat from the rib steak, why not use it as the saut medium for the home fries pommes frittes style?&nbsp; Or, if not enough oil, mix it with the olive oil.<br />
<span class='bbc_right'><a href='http://forums.egullet.org/index.php?app=forums&amp;module=forums&amp;section=findpost&amp;pid=1616185' class='bbc_url'><img src='http://forums.egullet.org/public/style_images/egullet/snapback.png' alt='View Post' /></a></span><br /></div></div><br />
<br />
I've tried that -- in the firm belief that it would be a brilliant innovation -- and just didn't like the flavor. The potatoes absorb a lot of fat and the flavor of rendered beef fat in that amount isn't to my liking. With the steak, which absorbs little fat, it's different. It would probably work well with duck fat or lard but for some reason beef fat is an outlier, at least to my palate.
						
						<br />
						
					</div>
					
