					<p class='posted_info'>
						
						
						Posted <abbr class="published" title="2008-11-11T17:51:11+00:00">11 November 2008 - 10:51 AM</abbr>
					</p>
					
					<div class='post entry-content '>
						<!--cached-Tue, 22 Feb 2011 03:09:22 +0000--><p class='citation'>sadistick, on Nov 10 2008, 07&#58;59 AM, said:</p><div class="blockquote"><div class='quote'>Very interesting....Especially when the top steak houses in Toronto all cook their steaks at super hot 800+ degree temps.<br />
<span class='bbc_right'><a href='http://forums.egullet.org/index.php?app=forums&amp;module=forums&amp;section=findpost&amp;pid=1616130' class='bbc_url'><img src='http://forums.egullet.org/public/style_images/egullet/snapback.png' alt='View Post' /></a></span><br /></div></div><br />
<br />
One problem with the Ducasse method, from a restaurant standpoint, is that it takes 45 minutes. That's just not acceptable for most restaurants, where they want to get your entrees on the table within about 30 minutes of you walking in the door. A 45-50 minute lag between ordering and receiving an entree only works in a Michelin three-star kind of setting where people are already planning for 2-3 hours in the restaurant. So it's understandable why steakhouses focus on quick-cooking methods. Which doesn't mean those methods are best.
						
						<br />
						
					</div>
					
