					<div class='post entry-content '>
						<!--cached-Tue, 22 Feb 2011 03:09:22 +0000--><p class='citation'>Holly Moore, on Nov 10 2008, 06&#58;47 PM, said:</p><div class="blockquote"><div class='quote'>your pic looks like a much better steak than the one in their pic. <br />
<span class='bbc_right'><a href='http://forums.egullet.org/index.php?app=forums&amp;module=forums&amp;section=findpost&amp;pid=1616185' class='bbc_url'><img src='http://forums.egullet.org/public/style_images/egullet/snapback.png' alt='View Post' /></a></span><br /></div></div><br />
<br />
The steak I got was one of the best-marbled steaks I've ever seen. It was butchered differently from the photo too -- no big bone sticking out, etc.<br />
<br />
One thing I should note, though, is that the quality of the steak does not affect the efficacy of this method. Thickness is the bigger issue. If you get a nice thick rib steak from the supermarket, this method works just as well. In other words, it will make that steak as good a steak as it can be.
						
						<br />
						
					</div>
					
