					<p class='posted_info'>
						
						
						Posted <abbr class="published" title="2008-11-11T18:00:05+00:00">11 November 2008 - 11:00 AM</abbr>
					</p>
					
					<div class='post entry-content '>
						<!--cached-Tue, 22 Feb 2011 03:09:22 +0000--><p class='citation'>jsmeeker, on Nov 10 2008, 04&#58;54 PM, said:</p><div class="blockquote"><div class='quote'>Is there any true difference between building up that level of brown goodness slowly vs. doing it quickly?<br />
<span class='bbc_right'><a href='http://forums.egullet.org/index.php?app=forums&amp;module=forums&amp;section=findpost&amp;pid=1616163' class='bbc_url'><img src='http://forums.egullet.org/public/style_images/egullet/snapback.png' alt='View Post' /></a></span><br /></div></div><br />
<br />
Quicker = higher heat. At some point you cross the line into charring, which is not the desired result. You also burn the butter. So you can speed it up a bit but not a ton.<br />
<br />
If you're cooking thinner steaks, quicker-cooking methods are I think most likely to give you a good crust while maintaining a pink interior, though I still recommend basting with butter at the end of cooking.
						
						<br />
						
					</div>
					
